<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-975-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 975 100.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 18 1989 v6 n50 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Free system board remedies output bug in IBM model 50Z. (PS/2microcomputer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sexton, Tara.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (quality control).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM PS-2 50 Z (Microcomputer) (defects).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersProduct FailuresBoards-CardsReplacement Policy.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Serial numbers of faulty system boards. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Tara SextonandM;IBM is offering a free system-board replacement to users of selected PS/2Model 50Z computers who encounter problems when sending data files to outputdevices, IBM officials said last week.andM;A bug in the system board of the Model 50Z can prevent such popular programsas Microsoft Corp.'s Windows and Lotus Development Corp.'s Symphony fromproperly accessing the PC's serial port, the officials said.andM;The bug occurs when software programs that bypass IBM's Model 50Z BIOSattempt to send data to a serial port, en route to output devices such asmodems, printers and plotters, said Cheryl Butcher, an IBM systems engineerin West Lafayette, Ind.andM;The bug is found only in the Model 50Z, a 286-based desktop machine that IBMtouts is its best-selling PS/2.andP;  It does not cause the system to crash, butsimply halts the output process.andM;Since finding the bug, IBM has issued an engineering change for its Model 50ZBIOS to prevent the bug from occurring in systems rolling off the productionline, Butcher said.andP;  IBM will also replace defective system boards (seechart) through the end of the year.andM;In addition to Windows and Symphony, the bug trips up several other popularprograms, including Microsoft's Word 5.0, and Lotus' Freelance, Graphwriterand 1-2-3 PostScript driver, IBM officials said.andM;Bruce Fuller, an electrical engineer at Purdue University, also in WestLafayette, said he discovered the bug when running Word 5.0 on theuniversity's machines.andP;  Word 4.0 had run without problems on 50Zs, he said.andM;&quot;Microsoft Word 5.0 worked fine on all of our other machines except the Model50Z,&quot; Fuller said.andM;Prior to IBM's disclosure of the system-board swap last week, &quot;the onlywork-around [was] to use Word 4.0, which is really not a solution,&quot; Fullersaid.andM;Users who have problems sending files through the 50Z's serial port, but whodon't qualify for a system-board replacement, can fix the bug by calling thesoftware developers for patches, Butcher said.andM;Microsoft, of Redmond, Wash., has already prepared debugged versions of Word5.0 and Windows, according to Jeff Sanderson, product manager for Word 5.0.andO;Users should contact Microsoft technical support to order a copy of the fix,he said.andM;IBM officials are recommending that users contact their local IBMrepresentative for assistance.andO;</TEXT></DOC>